name: 2,4-dichlorophenyl isothiocyanate

Typically, a chloro substituent can increase the melting point by approximately 20 degrees on a benzene ring. The isothiocyanate group (-N=C=S) is also a strong electron-withdrawing group due to the presence of nitrogen and sulfur atoms, which are connected by multiple bonds. This can further increase the melting point. The effect of an isothiocyanate group on the melting point is not as straightforward to quantify, but it could be significant and might raise the melting point by around 30 degrees. Combining these effects, we would predict an increase of about 70 degrees onto the base value of benzene.
